This paper is likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.CL (Computation and Language) as it deals with natural language processing and machine learning approaches for Native Language Identification (NLI). The paper also mentions the use of character p-grams and i-vectors, which are commonly used in NLP research. 

It is also likely to belong to the sub-category of cs.LG (Machine Learning) as the paper describes a machine learning approach for NLI. 

The sub-category of cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) is also a possibility as the paper deals with machine learning and natural language processing, which are both areas of AI research. 

The sub-category of cs.SD (Sound) is a possibility as the paper mentions the use of speech transcripts and i-vectors, which are related to audio recordings. 

Finally, the sub-category of cs.IR (Information Retrieval) is a possibility as the paper deals with identifying the native language of a speaker or writer, which is a task related to information retrieval.
